# Codex Prompt — Build the Aim Brain Engine Properly

Use this prompt when asking Codex to implement the real Aim Brain Engine.

```text
Build the Aim Brain Engine as a deterministic TypeScript logic layer separate from the UI.

Goal:
The app must become an actual coaching product, not only a dashboard. The UI should display analysis from the engine. React components must not contain analysis logic.

Create or update this structure:

src/engine/
  types/
  normalization/
  scenarios/
  ranks/
  stats/
  diagnosis/
  recommendations/
  coach/
  index.ts

Engine requirements:
1. Accept raw score runs, scenario data, threshold data, user goal, setup profiles, and current date.
2. Return one complete AimBrainResult object for the UI.
3. Calculate latest score, PB, all-run average, last-5 average, last-10 average, total runs, consistency, confidence, and trend.
4. Match scenarios using normalized names, aliases, platform, and safe fallback logic.
5. Convert score to rank only when threshold data exists.
6. For missing threshold data, return progress-only mode. Never invent ranks.
7. Detect strongest category, weakest category, most neglected category, most inconsistent category, and closest-to-rank-up category.
8. Detect plateau/decline/improvement only when enough recent data exists.
9. Recommend a training session with priority categories, recommended scenarios, reasons, session structure, and success condition.
10. Generate a rule-based coach summary from the engine output.

Important architecture rules:
- Do not put analysis logic in React components.
- Do not use AI or random behavior for calculations.
- Keep functions pure where possible.
- Make the same input produce the same output.
- Add sample data and tests for the core calculations.
- Keep manual score entry as fallback/debug only. Product direction is local automatic importing.

Start with a minimal but working engine. Do not overbuild. Implement the foundation first:
- types
- calculateScenarioStats
- calculateCategoryStats
- calculateRankProgress with missing-threshold fallback
- detectWeakCategories
- recommendTrainingSession
- generateCoachSummary
- analyzeAimProfile as the single public API

After implementation, update the UI to call:

import { analyzeAimProfile } from "@/engine";

The UI should render returned values and explanations, not recalculate them.
```
